            },
            "answer_text": "It doesn\u2019t quite say that. Rather, it says that for any effective set of axioms for your numbers, there will be a statement true for your numbers that can\u2019t be proved from those axioms. But there will be a larger set of axioms which can prove your true statement. In that larger set, there will be some other true statement that can\u2019t be proved, but, again, there\u2019s a still larger set of axioms in which it can be proved. So long as the axioms are effective, that is, they are recursively enumerable, there will be some statement that can\u2019t be proved. Recursively enumerable is a pretty weak requirement. It only requires that there is an algorithm to list all the axioms. There can even be infinitely many axioms. (For first-order number theory, you expect infinitely many axioms since the axiom of induction is actually an axiom schema. For each predicate, and there are infinitely many predicates, there is an axiom of induction.) Every true statement in number theory can be proved given the right set of axioms. ",
