            "answer_text": "Does G\u00f6del's incompleteness theorem mean that there are true statements that will never be proved? No, it doesn\u2019t. Although it is true that some, i.e. almost all, true arithmetic statements can never be proven by any axiomatic system. This is because axiomatic systems are very inefficient at capturing mathematical (arithmetical) truths. Thus once an axiomatic system is given, its demonstrative power is fixed once and for all. It can only prove statements of a given (Kolmogorov) complexity (length) that is characteristic of the system. From a probabilistic point of view, when the length of a statement tends towards infinity, the probability that the statement is independent tends towards 1. Adding recursively axioms that affirm the consistency of the chosen axiomatic system(s) will not change this. From a topological point of view, the set of arithmetical provable statements is just a big hole! Hence, I have to disagree with my distinguish colleague\u2019s (Dr. David Joyce) statement that: \"Every true statement in number theory can be proved given the right set of axioms.\" Because there is no such thing as the right set of axioms, if by right we mean a set of axioms that makes an axiomatic system complete for arithmetic. Addendum To put it in layman's terms, not only there are true statements that will never be proved, but since almost all statements in an axiomatic system that is rich enough to express elementary arithmetic (PA, ZFC, etc.) are independent statements, there are infinitely many true statements that will never be proved. If by \u201cnever\u201d we mean \u201ccannot\u201d. An by \u201ccannot\u201d we mean that there is no (known or conceivable) effective procedure to prove them. As previously mentioned, C. Calude has shown that there are infinitely many more independent statements than provable ones. Now, as L. Levin points out, in the abstract, if we consider all possible ways of adding axioms - in finite or infinite quantity - there are indeed some that give non-contradictory and complete \u201csystems\u201d. Thus, for any formula L of such systems, L can be either proved, or disproved, with these added axioms. The word \u201csystems\u201d in the previous sentence is enclosed in quotation marks because these complete axiom systems are not actual formal systems: it is certainly possible to add axioms in the abstract to the point of cramming the system with them so that we don't get any independent statements, but in this case the (effective or mechanical) verifiability of proofs of the resulting system is lost. If this was not the case, we'd have a system which would contradict G\u00f6del's theorem. Sources C. S. Calude et H. J\u00fcrgensen, Is complexity a source of incompleteness?, Advances in Applied Mathematics 35, pp.1-15, 2005: https://arxiv.org/pdf/math/04081... C. S. Calude, H. J\u00fcrgensenet M. Zimand, Is independence an exception?, Appl. Math.Comput. 66, pp.63-76, 1994: www.cs.auckland.ac.nz/~cristian/crispapers/independexception.pdf Leonid LEVIN, Forbidden information, The 43rd Annual IEEE Symposium on Foundations of Computer Science, 2002. Proceedings, pp.76-765: arxiv.org/pdf/cs/0203029.pdf L. Bienvenu et al., The axiomatic power of Kolmogorov complexity, Annals of Pure and Applied Logic, 2013: arxiv.org/pdf/1301.3392.pdf Claude Taillefer's answer to What does it mean that we need better axioms if a problem is independent of system X? What more axioms could we possibly add when we added all there is? ",
