            "answer_text": "As a statement, G\u00f6del's incompleteness theorem does not state such. But there are two related issues with G\u00f6del's 1931 Incompleteness paper: His alleged theorem is invalid per Nam Nguyen\u2019s answer in this Quora Thread.It can be shown (and has been shown in sci.logic) that neither the FOL sentence \u201cThere are infinitely many counter examples of Goldbach conjecture\u201d nor its negation can possibly be proven (conceptually conceived) to be true of the concept of \u201cnatural numbers\u201d.The sentence mentioned in 2. pertains to the class of [arithmetic] \u201cstatements that will never be proved\u201d (referred to in the title-question of the thread): simply because these FOPL (First Order Predicate Logic) sentences don\u2019t have relevant truth values. ",
