            "answer_text": "There is some controversy over whether it should be interpreted even that strongly\u2026 but it is the interpretation that Godel himself gave the theorems, as well as John Von Newman (possibly the most accomplished mathematician of the 20th Century), who in a sense \u201cdiscovered\u201d Godel. What people have to agree on is that for any given formal system of Number Theory, there will be some propositions that can be neither proved nor disproved. However, through Godel numbering, such a proposition can be seen to have a logical equivalence to a proposition that says \u201cI am not provable.\u201d Now, here\u2019s the tricky part: the proposition doesn\u2019t *literally* say that; but Godel Numbering sets up a relationship such that proposition G is true if and only if it is not provable. Because it isn\u2019t provable, simple logic would suggest it is true. (The one additional assumption, by the way, is that the whole system is self-consistent.) That being the case, I personally do tend to accept Godel\u2019s own interpretation of his theorems. So, there is a proposition (an infinite number of them, actually) that are true but not provable. ",
